def big_cutting(higgs,qcd,low_bound, high_bound, feature):
    higgs_cut = cutting(higgscut_dict, low_bound, high_bound,feature) 
    qcd_cut = cutting(qcdcut_dict, low_bound, high_bound,feature)
    higgs_yield = len(higgs_cut)/len(higgs_dict)  * 50
    qcd_yield  = len(qcd_cut)/len(qcd_dict)  * 2000
    print(higgs_yield)
    print(qcd_yield)
    print("The expected significance is: ", higgs_yield/np.sqrt(qcd_yield))
In [2]:
def cut_helper(data,low_bound,high_bound,original):
    x_val = (data['mass'] > low_bound) & (data['mass'] < high_bound)
    y_val = data[x_val]
    ratio = len(y_val)/len(data)
    output = original * ratio
    return output
In [3]:
def cutting(data,low_bound, high_bound, feature):
    x_val = (data > low_bound) & (data< high_bound)
    y_val = data[x_val]
    return y_val

# this cutting method is for lab 8, since it is similar to the  cutting method above
# I put this cutting method here for covenience
def all_cutting(data,low_bound, high_bound):
    x_val = (data > low_bound) & (data < high_bound)
    y_val = data[x_val]
    return y_val

Since the difference is around 0.01, I would say that they are the same numerically. However, they have some difference conceptually. When the poisson distribution has a large parameter $\lambda$, it can be approximated by Gaussian with parameters,$\lambda$ and sqrt( $\lambda$), since the sum equals n_higgs + n_qcd, the formula for the significance are the same.
